George McGovern, Comeback Kid

This was a victory decades in the making. You've completely routed Bush with a victory margin strikingly opposed to your loss 20 years ago. The entire country has been left confused and bewildered - the rumors of a comeback may have been believed by some, but no one ever thought you would win in a bona fide landslide against an incumbent that had just won a war. Perhaps the economy was too bad, or you had really learned and grown from 1972, like you said early in the year.

Nonetheless, this momentous victory is celebrated by your entire campaign, your family, and liberals across the nation. America came home - it's a shame it only took 20 years.

It's '72 All Over Again

The political columns read this on the day after the election. You've lost in a landslide - again, dredging up memories of your campaign 20 years ago. You watched Bush, upon being notified of his win, walk up in front of cheering voters, who no doubt feel vindicated of the Republican Party's triumph over the old liberal majority. And there you sat, after your call with him, defeated. But you don't take it too hard - you never wanted this anyways.

It looked for a second that you would have broken the consensus on you built by your loss in 1972, but the label of one of the biggest losers in American politics is going to stick - and it's going to be worse than Mondale's. Whatever you did, it just didn't seem to work - Bush might have been too powerful and his re-election a foregone conclusion, like many thought in the wake of the Gulf War.

Your political career is hereby over - its grave was dug in 1980, and you are finally happy to let it go. But you will not stop fighting for what you believe in as you return to lecturing - maybe the next Democratic president will give you an appointment?

Good luck, Mr. McGovern.

20 Years Later, George McGovern Enters the White House

This is what the papers read on election night. Everyone across the nation is surprised - this wasn't what was predicted back when President Bush was seen as invulnerable in 1991. Electoral College Deadlocks - President Undecided

This is the worst end to an election season to everyone. The electoral college vote has ended in deadlock, with neither you nor Bush achieving the required 270 for a majority.
